{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525641"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14090"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14090"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.37,0.17,0.4,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14090"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"2891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44407"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of swelling and pain on the lower left side of her face. She reports feeling generally unwell with a mild fever and headache. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is visible swelling over the left parotid gland (see Image), which is tender to palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral pharyngitis","Bacterial parotitis","Sialolithiasis","Mumps","Cervical lymphadenopathy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of unilateral parotid gland swelling, pain, and systemic symptoms such as fever and headache is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Emumps\u003C/strong\u003E. Mumps is a viral infection caused by the mumps virus, which primarily affects the salivary glands, particularly the parotid glands. The swelling and tenderness of the parotid gland, along with mild systemic symptoms, are classic signs of mumps. It is typically bilateral parotid swelling, but can be unilateral. Although mumps is less common in adults due to widespread vaccination, it can still occur, especially in unvaccinated individuals or those with waning immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial parotitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with unilateral swelling and is often associated with more severe systemic symptoms, such as high fever and purulent discharge from the duct. The patient would likely appear more unwell, and there might be erythema over the gland. The mild systemic symptoms and the absence of purulent discharge in this case make bacterial parotitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialolithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the presence of salivary stones, which usually cause unilateral gland swelling and pain, often associated with eating due to obstruction of saliva flow. The systemic symptoms such as fever and headache are not typical of sialolithiasis, making this diagnosis less likely in the context of the presented symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E involves swelling of the lymph nodes in the neck, which can occur due to various infections or conditions. However, it does not typically cause the characteristic parotid gland swelling seen in mumps. The location and nature of the swelling in this case are more consistent with parotid gland involvement rather than lymph node enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sore throat and systemic symptoms like fever, but it does not typically cause parotid gland swelling. The presence of unilateral parotid swelling, along with the specific location of the pain and swelling, makes mumps a more likely diagnosis than viral pharyngitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mumps is a viral infection that primarily affects the parotid glands, leading to swelling and pain.","Diagnosis of mumps is primarily clinical, supported by the presence of parotid gland swelling and systemic symptoms."],"references":["Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. Australian Immunisation Handbook - Mumps. Australian Government. 2023. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/mumps","Su SB, Chang HL, Chen AK. Current Status of Mumps Virus Infection: Epidemiology, Pathogenesis, and Vaccine. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2020 Mar 5;17(5):1686. doi: 10.3390/ijerph17051686. PMID: 32150969; PMCID: PMC7084951.","Balbi AM, Van Sant AA, Bean EW, Jacoby JL. Mumps: Resurgence of a once-dormant disease. JAAPA. 2018 May;31(5):19-22. doi: 10.1097/01.JAA.0000532112.90755.41. PMID: 29642091."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14090"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20982"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20982"},"attributes":